  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What is the best open-source captive portal for a WiFi Hospot?",
  "response": "When setting up a WiFi hotspot with a captive portal, selecting the right open-source solution depends on your specific needs, such as scalability, ease of use, feature set, and community support. Here are some of the best open-source captive portal solutions to consider:\n\n### 1. **pfSense**\n\n![pfSense Logo](https://www.pfsense.org/images/hero-pfsense.png)\n\n**Overview:**\npfSense is a powerful, open-source firewall and router platform based on FreeBSD. It includes a built-in captive portal feature that is highly customizable and suitable for various deployment scenarios.\n\n**Key Features:**\n- **Comprehensive Firewall Capabilities:** Beyond captive portal functionality, pfSense offers robust network security features.\n- **User Authentication:** Supports multiple authentication methods, including local user databases, RADIUS, and captive portal vouchers.\n- **Customization:** Offers extensive customization options for login pages, session management, and bandwidth control.\n- **Scalability:** Suitable for both small deployments and large-scale environments.\n- **Active Community & Documentation:** Extensive support through forums, documentation, and community-contributed packages.\n\n**Pros:**\n- All-in-one solution combining firewall, routing, and captive portal.\n- Highly secure with regular updates.\n- Flexible and scalable for different sizes of deployments.\n\n**Cons:**\n- Can be resource-intensive for smaller setups.\n- Steeper learning curve for beginners.\n\n**Website:** [pfSense](https://www.pfsense.org/)\n\n### 2. **CoovaChilli**\n\n![CoovaChilli Logo](https://coova.org/img/coovachilli.jpg)\n\n**Overview:**\nCoovaChilli is an open-source access controller for captive portal systems, designed to work seamlessly with various authentication methods and backend systems like FreeRADIUS.\n\n**Key Features:**\n- **RADIUS Support:** Integrates well with RADIUS servers for centralized authentication.\n- **Flexibility:** Highly configurable to suit different network environments.\n- **Bandwidth Management:** Allows for bandwidth throttling and usage policies.\n- **Compatibility:** Works with a wide range of hardware and software platforms.\n\n**Pros:**\n- Highly customizable and flexible.\n- Strong integration capabilities with existing authentication systems.\n- Lightweight and efficient.\n\n**Cons:**\n- Configuration can be complex for users unfamiliar with networking concepts.\n- Documentation may sometimes be sparse or technical.\n\n**Website:** [CoovaChilli](https://coova.github.io/CoovaChilli/)\n\n### 3. **nodogsplash**\n\n![nodogsplash Logo](https://www.nodogsplash.com/images/logo_white.png)\n\n**Overview:**\nnodogsplash is a lightweight, easy-to-deploy captive portal solution ideal for smaller networks or environments where simplicity is key.\n\n**Key Features:**\n- **Simplicity:** Easy to set up with minimal configuration required.\n- **Lightweight:** Consumes fewer resources, making it suitable for low-power devices.\n- **Customizable Splash Pages:** Allows for basic customization of the landing page.\n- **Auto-Login:** Supports auto-login for frequent users if desired.\n\n**Pros:**\n- Quick and straightforward installation process.\n- Minimal resource usage.\n- Ideal for small to medium-sized deployments.\n\n**Cons:**\n- Limited features compared to more robust solutions like pfSense or CoovaChilli.\n- Less suitable for larger, more complex networks.\n\n**Website:** [nodogsplash](https://nodogsplash.github.io/)\n\n### 4. **WifiDog**\n\n![WifiDog Logo](https://sourceforge.net/p/wifidog/logo/WifiDog_logo_small.png)\n\n**Overview:**\nWifiDog is an open-source captive portal solution designed to provide a community-driven hotspot experience. It focuses on ease of use and offers features like per-user bandwidth limits and billing integration.\n\n**Key Features:**\n- **Community Hotspot Support:** Facilitates community-driven wireless networks.\n- **User Management:** Supports user authentication and billing.\n- **Extensible:** Can be extended with additional plugins and modules.\n\n**Pros:**\n- Suitable for community and public hotspot deployments.\n- Provides user management and billing features out-of-the-box.\n- Active development and support community.\n\n**Cons:**\n- May be overkill for simple deployments.\n- Configuration can be more involved compared to simpler solutions like nodogsplash.\n\n**Website:** [WifiDog](http://wifidog.org/)\n\n### 5. **OpenWRT with Captive Portal Packages**\n\n**Overview:**\nOpenWRT is a flexible, open-source firmware for routers that can be extended with various packages to implement captive portal functionality.\n\n**Key Features:**\n- **Modular Design:** Allows installation of specific packages like `nodogsplash`, `CoovaChilli`, or others to enable captive portals.\n- **Customizability:** High degree of customization based on installed packages and configurations.\n- **Wide Hardware Support:** Compatible with a vast range of router hardware.\n\n**Pros:**\n- Highly customizable to fit unique requirements.\n- Leverages the stability and flexibility of OpenWRT.\n- Active community support with extensive documentation.\n\n**Cons:**\n- Requires familiarity with OpenWRT and Linux-based systems.\n- Setup can be more time-consuming compared to turnkey solutions.\n\n**Website:** [OpenWRT](https://openwrt.org/)\n\n### **Recommendation**\n\nFor most use cases, **pfSense** stands out as the best open-source captive portal solution due to its comprehensive feature set, robustness, and active community support. It not only provides captive portal capabilities but also offers extensive networking and security features, making it suitable for both small and large deployments.\n\nHowever, if you require a more lightweight and simpler solution, especially for smaller networks, **nodogsplash** or **CoovaChilli** might be more appropriate. For users already leveraging OpenWRT on their hardware, extending it with captive portal packages offers a flexible and integrated approach.\n\n### **Conclusion**\n\nChoosing the \"best\" open-source captive portal depends on your specific requirements, including the scale of deployment, desired features, and your comfort level with configuration and maintenance. **pfSense** is generally recommended for its robustness and feature richness, but alternatives like **CoovaChilli**, **nodogsplash**, and solutions based on **OpenWRT** are also excellent choices based on different needs and scenarios.",
